# 43_run_context_gating - exercises the two structural rules in m5c
# (ARC's security architecture, Tier 5). Closes the m5c arc opened
# by s244 m1's path_is_safe utility. Tier 5 row ticks 0/2 -> 2/2 on
# this smoke's clean pass.
#
# ── What this Scriptable surface is for ──────────────────────────────────
#
# m5c lands two structural rules in the script engine. Neither has a
# user-facing observable on its own - they live in the dispatcher
# plumbing under the m5b headless-verb singletons that will ship
# next:
#
#   1. Path containment (s244 m1): scripted callers that take a path
#      argument resolve the path through realpath() and refuse unless
#      the resolved absolute path is under $HOME or $TMPDIR. The
#      utility (curvz::scripting::path_is_safe) is init'd once at
#      Application::on_startup and called once per sensitive verb.
#
#   2. RunContext gating (s244 m2): every verb declares a bitmask of
#      caller contexts (TestRunner / Macro / Scripter) permitted to
#      invoke it. The dispatcher checks the caller's context against
#      the mask on every invoke. Default mask is all-three so every
#      existing verb stays callable.
#
# Both rules are exercised here through the diagnostic surface on
# `inspector` (s244 m2):
#
#   query  home_root                  - cached $HOME root (string)
#   query  tmp_root                   - cached $TMPDIR root (string)
#   query  home_root_initialised      - bool (assertable)
#   query  tmp_root_initialised       - bool (assertable)
#   query  home_root_is_safe          - bool, accept-side
#   query  tmp_root_is_safe           - bool, accept-side
#   query  etc_is_safe                - bool, refuse-side (/etc/passwd)
#   query  slash_is_safe              - bool, refuse-side (/)
#   query  empty_is_safe              - bool, refuse-side ("")
#   verb   diagnose_universal         - returns "ok" (universal mask)
#   verb   diagnose_test_runner_only  - TestRunner mask only
#
# path_is_safe coverage is provided through queries (not a verb
# taking a path arg) so each case is `assert`-able - the DSL's
# `assert` form is equality-on-query-result.
#
# ── Test isolation ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# No mutation. All queries pull from process-immutable cached state
# or are pure reads of path_is_safe with hardcoded paths. The two
# verbs are stateless (return strings). The smoke is repeatable
# without setup or teardown.
#
# ── Caller context ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# This smoke runs through ScripterWindow's listener, which sets its
# m_context to RunContext::Scripter at ctor (s244 m2 wiring in
# ScripterWindow.cpp). Every verb invocation here therefore comes
# from the Scripter context. The accept-path observable
# (diagnose_universal) is a verb whose mask includes Scripter; the
# refuse-path observable (diagnose_test_runner_only) is gated to
# TestRunner only and is refused by the dispatcher BEFORE its body
# runs.
#
# The refusal is visible in the trace as:
#
#   > inspector diagnose_test_runner_only
#   error invoke refused: verb 'diagnose_test_runner_only' on
#   'inspector' not permitted in scripter context
#
# The DSL's `assert` is equality-only, so this negative-path check
# is not assertable directly - the operator confirms by reading the
# error line in the output. Same convention as 42_palettes' miss
# case (`palettes find_by_name "no_such_palette"`). The summary's
# error count will be 1 when this smoke passes - that single error
# IS the dispatcher gating working as designed.

#[sub] === Phase 1: path_is_safe init verification ===

#[sub] init_roots() runs once in Application::on_startup. The
#[sub] cached HOME / TMP roots survive for the process's lifetime.
#[sub] Both should be populated by the time the smoke runs.

get inspector home_root
get inspector tmp_root
assert inspector home_root_initialised == true
assert inspector tmp_root_initialised == true

#[sub] === Phase 2: path_is_safe acceptance ===

#[sub] Accept: home_root and tmp_root ARE the cached roots, so they
#[sub] must be safe by construction (equal to the prefix they're
#[sub] checked against). These are the trivial accept cases that
#[sub] confirm the predicate behaves on its own inputs.

assert inspector home_root_is_safe == true
assert inspector tmp_root_is_safe == true

#[sub] === Phase 3: path_is_safe refusal ===

#[sub] Refuse: /etc/passwd is universally outside $HOME and /tmp on
#[sub] any Linux FHS install. Realpath resolves through any /etc
#[sub] symlink, then the prefix check refuses.

assert inspector etc_is_safe == false

#[sub] Refuse: the filesystem root. Strictly shallower than either
#[sub] cached root by construction; prefix check refuses.

assert inspector slash_is_safe == false

#[sub] Refuse: empty path. The degenerate case path_is_safe handles
#[sub] at the top of the predicate with the "empty path" reason.

assert inspector empty_is_safe == false

#[sub] === Phase 4: RunContext gating accept ===

#[sub] Accept: a verb whose mask includes Scripter (the default
#[sub] all-three mask, inherited from Scriptable's base). The
#[sub] dispatcher's gating check passes and the verb's body runs,
#[sub] returning "ok". Verb returns are not directly assertable
#[sub] via the DSL's equality-only `assert`, so this is operator-
#[sub] visual: read the `= "ok"` echo line in the trace after the
#[sub] line below.

inspector diagnose_universal

#[sub] === Phase 5: RunContext gating refuse ===

#[sub] Refuse: a verb gated to TestRunner only. From Scripter
#[sub] context, the dispatcher refuses BEFORE the verb's body
#[sub] runs. The expected trace line is:
#[sub]
#[sub]   error invoke refused: verb 'diagnose_test_runner_only'
#[sub]   on 'inspector' not permitted in scripter context
#[sub]
#[sub] The DSL has no equality-comparable "did the last line
#[sub] error" predicate, so this is operator-visual: read the
#[sub] line below this comment in the trace and confirm the
#[sub] refusal appears. The smoke's summary line at end will
#[sub] show 1 error (this one), which IS the gating working as
#[sub] designed.

inspector diagnose_test_runner_only

#[sub] === Phase 6: post-refusal sanity ===

#[sub] After the refused invoke, the listener should be in a
#[sub] clean state. A subsequent legitimate invoke must succeed
#[sub] (the refuse path is a structured early-return, not a
#[sub] listener-level error that corrupts dispatch state).
#[sub] Operator-visual again - watch for `= "ok"` below.

inspector diagnose_universal

#[sub] s244 m2 smoke complete. Expected summary line: 7 PASSes
#[sub] (init verify x2, path_is_safe accept x2, path_is_safe
#[sub] refuse x3) and 1 error (the diagnose_test_runner_only
#[sub] refusal - intentional). Operator-visual on the two
#[sub] diagnose_universal `= "ok"` echoes (accept-path and
#[sub] post-refuse sanity). m5c arc closes; Tier 5 row ticks
#[sub] 0/2 -> 2/2.
